			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2009</a> keynote:</span><br><i>Eating Our Own Dog Food: DSLs for Generative and Transformational Engineering</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/JamesRCordy.html">James R. Cordy</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_1">10.1007/978-3-642-12107-4_1</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagM">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> Keynote advocates designing domain-specific languages to make generative and transformational techniques more accessible and reusable.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It frames practical use of transformation systems and proposes DSLs tailored to specific transformation/analysis tasks.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It discusses generative uses (code generation) as a major application domain for such DSLs.
</li></ul></li></ul>
